  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Increasing safe and dignified living conditions through provision of emergency shelter and cash for winterization to internally displaced persons (IDPs) affected by drought in Herat province.</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">DRC, through this project, aims to deliver emergency shelter kits (family sized tent with necessary tools for pitching and 2 Tarpaulins) and winterization to support drought-affected internally displaced people who live in open spaces and makeshift shelters that do not provide dignity, privacy and protection from the elements.
DRC participated in the inter-agency joint assessments between May and July 2018, verified 11,802 displaced families (82,614 individuals) and distributed cash for food to a total of 7,122 families while the remaining caseload (4,892 families) was covered by Norwegian Refugee Council (NRC). 
Through Afghanistan Humanitarian Fund (AHF) 3rd Reserve Allocation, DRC is carrying out the distribution of 2,200 emergency shelter kits. Through additional inter-agency assessments and verifications, the total number of internally displaced people rose by 10,000 households. As of November first, the total number of households living in informal sites in Injil district stood at 20186  (141302 individuals). DRC plans to distribute 4,326 family tents, procured by UNHCR, and cash for winterization to 7573 displaced families living at Injil IDP settlements in Herat province.
A team of community volunteers has been identified, trained on shelter program and in turn provide support to female-headed families, families with large number children, disabled and critical illness in the erection of shelters. 
To ensure service provision in a dignified manner, DRC has an accountability framework as part of its action plan to comply with common humanitarian standards (CHS) that will be used as a benchmark to guide its quality implementation along with ES/NFI cluster guidelines. Shelter is a key protection priority. This project will have a direct impact on the protective environment in informal IDP settlements. DRC will mainstream protection throughout project implementation to minimize secondary protection risks.

The project duration is 4 months, active from 24 November 2018 to 23 March 2019.</narrative>
  </description>
